    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I'm actually looking at a specific section right now regarding \"indemnification\" and \"third-party claims.\" It's a bit dense. Could you explain what it actually means for my personal liability if I accidentally breach one of these clauses? Like, what kind of risks am I looking at?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Indemnification clauses are essentially a promise that you will pay for the other party's losses if a specific event happens, often triggered by your actions or negligence. If you accidentally breach an indemnification clause, you could face significant financial liability, potentially covering legal fees, damages, or even the entire cost of a lawsuit filed by the other party. Third-party claims add another layer of complexity because they can arise from issues outside the direct contract, such as a product defect or a breach of a separate agreement, which can expose you to unexpected lawsuits. The risk here is that the other party can use these clauses to shift the burden of their own mistakes or unforeseen events onto you, leading to substantial out-of-pocket expenses. It is vital to understand the scope of your liability, as these clauses can be quite broad and might catch you off guard if not carefully reviewed.",
      "source": "target",
